WEBVTT

00:01.346 --> 00:01.867
Good morning.

00:03.208 --> 00:03.909
My name is Scott.

00:03.929 --> 00:07.373
I'm one of the pastors here at Perdido Bay Methodist Church and welcome.

00:08.094 --> 00:12.659
We're preaching our stewardship series about how God has been faithful to us.

00:12.719 --> 00:14.321
God has been faithful in the past.

00:14.862 --> 00:16.123
God is faithful today.

00:16.183 --> 00:18.206
God will be faithful in the future.

00:19.307 --> 00:24.913
Levi preached last week about God's faithfulness in the past, and he's asked me to preach about God's faithfulness today.

00:24.974 --> 00:28.818
Stewardship is simply where the means that we are

00:28.962 --> 00:37.793
faithful with all that God entrusts to us, God entrusts resources to us, and we manage it well because all that we have and all that we are really belongs to God.

00:38.654 --> 00:51.189
And in this series, especially next Sunday, we'll have our pledge Sunday where we ask church members to pledge to give towards our budget so that we're able to do together what God is calling us to do.

00:52.210 --> 00:55.954
And today the focus is on how God is faithful to us today.

00:55.975 --> 00:58.898
The basis of our sermon series

00:59.074 --> 01:07.604
is the scripture verse in Hebrews chapter 13 verse eight that says, Jesus Christ is the same yesterday, today, and forever.

01:09.185 --> 01:14.371
And to help us remember that Jesus is faithful today, we're gonna look at two scripture verses.

01:14.792 --> 01:18.536
The first one is earlier in the letter to the Hebrews.

01:18.796 --> 01:27.346
In chapter three, the writer of Hebrews comments on Psalm 95, and he writes the following, he says,

01:28.770 --> 01:35.940
Take care, brothers and sisters, that none of you may have an evil, unbelieving heart that turns away from the living God.

01:37.162 --> 01:48.557
But exhort one another every day, as long as it is called today, so that none of you may be hardened by the deceitfulness of sin, for we have become partners of Christ.

01:49.479 --> 01:57.810
If only we hold our first confidence firm to the end, as it is said today,

01:58.178 --> 02:02.245
If you hear his voice, do not harden your hearts as in the day of rebellion.

02:04.188 --> 02:09.136
The Apostle Paul, in his second letter to the Corinthians, sums up the gospel in a wonderful way.

02:09.176 --> 02:16.227
And when he sums it up, he calls us to respond to God in words very similar to what the writer Hebrew says.

02:17.549 --> 02:20.755
Paul writes in 2 Corinthians 5, beginning with verse 17.

02:21.836 --> 02:25.362
So if anyone is in Christ, there is a new creation.

02:26.082 --> 02:27.583
Everything old has passed away.

02:27.623 --> 02:30.266
Look, new things have come into being.

02:30.306 --> 02:38.113
All this is from God who reconciled us to Himself through Christ and has given us the ministry of reconciliation.

02:39.314 --> 02:49.444
That is, in Christ, God was reconciling the world to Himself, not counting their trespasses against them, and entrusting the message of reconciliation to us.

02:51.086 --> 02:55.890
So we are ambassadors for Christ since God is making His appeal through us

02:56.226 --> 02:58.229
We entreat you on behalf of Christ.

02:58.810 --> 03:00.051
Be reconciled to God.

03:01.013 --> 03:07.662
For our sake, God made him who knew no sin to be sin so that in him we might become the righteousness of God.

03:08.724 --> 03:15.614
As we work together with him, we entreat you also not to accept the grace of God in vain.

03:16.575 --> 03:20.020
For it says, at an acceptable time, I have listened to you.

03:20.060 --> 03:22.864
And on a day of salvation, I have helped you.

03:23.786 --> 03:24.146
Look,

03:24.514 --> 03:26.356
Now is the acceptable time.

03:27.257 --> 03:30.300
Look, now is the day of salvation.

03:31.601 --> 03:32.262
Let us pray.

03:35.385 --> 03:52.722
Faithful and loving God, pour your Holy Spirit upon all of us, upon me so that I'll have the strength to faithfully proclaim the words you have given me, and upon all of us so that our thoughts will be pleasing and acceptable to you.

03:53.986 --> 03:56.389
who are our rock and redeemer.

03:57.230 --> 03:57.611
Amen.

04:03.920 --> 04:04.821
My message is simple.

04:05.101 --> 04:08.406
God is faithful to us today, today.

04:08.706 --> 04:10.649
Therefore, we practice stewardship.

04:10.709 --> 04:20.182
We practice faithfulness with what God entrusts us today, not just we did it in the past, and not just we'll wait until the future to do it.

04:20.823 --> 04:23.186
We are faithful stewards today.

04:25.090 --> 04:30.275
I came across a wonderful prayer in one of my prayer books by a guy named William Macy.

04:30.295 --> 04:35.400
This was from way back in 1935, and it actually is a poem prayer.

04:35.961 --> 04:39.825
And he wrote, so let me face the future unafraid.

04:41.166 --> 04:44.750
Today is good, tomorrow taunts with fear.

04:46.011 --> 04:52.818
Tomorrow I shall find God's today to prove a new His presence near.

04:53.538 --> 05:01.168
That prayer is really guided and shaped by the words that Jesus gives us in this Sermon on the Mount.

05:01.989 --> 05:04.493
Remember, Jesus tells us not to worry about the future.

05:04.553 --> 05:20.594
So in Matthew chapter six, beginning with verse 32, Jesus says, your heavenly Father knows that you need all these things, but seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness and all these things will be given to you as well.

05:21.250 --> 05:26.816
So do not worry about tomorrow, for tomorrow we'll bring worries of its own.

05:27.317 --> 05:29.499
Today's trouble is enough for today.

05:29.979 --> 05:31.661
Jesus tells us to be focused on today.

05:31.721 --> 05:33.103
Don't worry about tomorrow.

05:33.163 --> 05:36.867
Focus on what's going on today.

05:36.887 --> 05:45.316
One of my spiritual directors, Elaine Mao, she gave me a wonderful prayer to pray, says, Lord, what I need you've given me today.

05:45.336 --> 05:48.860
And for what you've given me today, Lord, I give you thanks.

05:48.900 --> 05:50.802
She taught me to pray that way.

05:52.674 --> 05:58.787
And when we pray the Lord's prayer, don't we say, give us this day, this day?

05:58.847 --> 06:05.400
Or we can say, actually, in the Greek of the prayer in the New Testament, it's give us the bread of today.

06:05.480 --> 06:08.206
Give us this day our daily bread.

06:08.226 --> 06:10.290
We don't pray, Lord, give us

06:10.754 --> 06:18.904
Our bread for next month, Lord, give us our bread for next year or the next five years so we can store it up so we'll know that we'll be taken care of.

06:18.964 --> 06:20.606
Now we trust God each day.

06:20.667 --> 06:23.110
Give us this day our daily bread.

06:23.170 --> 06:27.555
So today we don't harden our hearts.

06:27.615 --> 06:29.478
We practice good stewardship.

06:31.240 --> 06:33.463
Now is the acceptable time.

06:34.264 --> 06:36.146
Now is the day of salvation.

06:39.650 --> 06:45.959
We practice stewardship today, and we do not get stuck in what we did in the past.

06:45.979 --> 06:52.449
We can get stuck in ways that are maybe positive or maybe negative in the positive way.

06:52.469 --> 06:58.678
We remember the good that God has done for us.

06:58.719 --> 07:01.042
Levi preached last week about how God has

07:01.282 --> 07:02.524
has been faithful to us.

07:02.564 --> 07:09.775
God, it's true God has been faithful to us in so many ways, not just to us, but to our ancestors, to previous generations of the church.

07:10.416 --> 07:17.326
We remember and celebrate how God has been faithful, especially when we go through tough times.

07:17.406 --> 07:27.101
When we face moments of doubt and struggle, we can recount and remember how God has been faithful in the past, and that will encourage us, that will strengthen our faith.

07:28.062 --> 07:30.546
But we don't get stuck in what we did in the past,

07:31.298 --> 07:33.660
Either the good things we've done are in our failures.

07:34.621 --> 07:44.331
The best advice I was given about preaching or any other act of ministry was that when I'm finished with it, I just had it over to God.

07:44.371 --> 07:48.975
I don't pat myself on the back layer saying, well, Scott, you did such a great job.

07:48.995 --> 07:49.896
You're so wonderful.

07:49.956 --> 07:51.318
I'm not to do that.

07:51.958 --> 07:54.000
And I'm not to beat myself up for my mistakes.

07:54.020 --> 07:55.622
I'm not to say, you know, why did I do that?

07:55.722 --> 07:56.703
Why did I say that?

07:57.103 --> 07:59.826
Oh, that was so bad.

08:00.130 --> 08:02.954
simply to let it go and let God deal with it.

08:04.696 --> 08:06.038
We don't get stuck in the past.

08:07.019 --> 08:13.188
And you could wonder, well, Scott, aren't we supposed to learn from what we've done in the past?

08:13.228 --> 08:24.323
And of course, we can debrief, we can recount and learn from what we've done wrong, and also from what we've done right.

08:25.124 --> 08:26.165
Football players do that.

08:26.185 --> 08:29.810
They watch film of their previous games, so they can learn.

08:30.338 --> 08:32.300
from their mistakes and learn from what they did well.

08:32.701 --> 08:38.808
So we learn from the past, our past and other people's past, but we don't dwell on it.

08:39.629 --> 08:40.690
We don't stay in it.

08:41.471 --> 08:42.473
We don't get stuck in it.

08:42.493 --> 08:43.714
Do you see the difference?

08:45.516 --> 08:55.648
Now for those of us who've been involved in the Cairo's prison ministry, there's a wonderful story that Cairo's has that we share during the Cairo's weekend about someone getting stuck in the past.

08:55.709 --> 08:56.890
And I want to share it with you too.

08:56.930 --> 08:58.632
It's not my story, it's from Cairo's.

08:59.053 --> 09:00.274
It's called the rooster.

09:00.706 --> 09:11.683
It's about a farmer who had this prized rooster that he brought to different country fairs, and he won Blue Ribbon's first prizes, and he loved that rooster.

09:11.723 --> 09:15.990
And the farmer also had a 16-year-old son whom he loved.

09:16.931 --> 09:22.340
And when the son turned 16, he wanted a new car, a red convertible.

09:23.161 --> 09:28.850
And he kept nagging his father forward and father finally got him a red convertible.

09:29.058 --> 09:32.982
The son, he would, actually, he was not that mature because he would drive around recklessly.

09:33.042 --> 09:35.864
He would do donuts in the parking lot.

09:35.904 --> 09:38.146
He would drive his friends around fast.

09:38.787 --> 09:45.193
And then he was coming home late, past curfew one night, just zooming down the road and zooming into the driveway.

09:45.213 --> 09:46.554
And he hid the brakes.

09:47.175 --> 09:49.717
And he slammed into the chicken coop.

09:49.737 --> 09:51.799
And he killed his father's rooster.

09:52.880 --> 09:59.026
And he was heartbroken because he knew how much his father loved that rooster.

09:59.202 --> 10:09.155
He got out of his car and he saw the feathers there and the dead bird on his hood and he saw his father standing on the porch.

10:09.956 --> 10:14.261
And he carried the rooster to his father with tears on his eyes because he knew he heard his father.

10:15.122 --> 10:17.665
And he said, I'm sorry.

10:17.825 --> 10:21.130
And the father said, I'm disappointed, but I forgive you.

10:22.391 --> 10:24.554
Get a shovel and bury the rooster.

10:25.014 --> 10:26.056
And so that's what the son did.

10:26.076 --> 10:27.858
He buried it under

10:28.002 --> 10:30.044
the shade of a tree that was close by.

10:30.064 --> 10:37.913
Three days later, he was driving home and he began to think about what he'd done wrong and started feeling real guilty again.

10:37.974 --> 10:41.538
So when he got home, he went and got the shovel and he dug up the rooster.

10:42.138 --> 10:49.667
And this time with the carcass of the rooster starting to rot, he went and found his father working in the barn and said, Dad, I'm so sorry for what I've done.

10:49.707 --> 10:51.149
Please forgive me.

10:51.209 --> 10:53.752
And the father said, I've already forgiven you.

10:53.772 --> 10:55.634
Go bury the rooster.

10:56.962 --> 11:00.567
A week later, he was driving, he kind of felt bad again about what he did.

11:00.727 --> 11:03.931
So again, he found where the rooster was buried.

11:03.951 --> 11:09.239
He took a shovel, buried it, and undugged him, and carried him again to the father, and said, Father, please forgive me.

11:09.279 --> 11:12.423
And the father said, look, son, I've already forgiven you.

11:12.463 --> 11:13.965
Let it go.

11:13.985 --> 11:16.448
Go back and bury the rooster.

11:16.528 --> 11:18.171
It's a story about how God forgives us.

11:18.711 --> 11:20.614
And we just got to accept God's forgiveness.

11:20.894 --> 11:23.157
But sometimes we get stuck in the past.

11:23.177 --> 11:26.642
We get stuck about our failures, and we keep bringing them to God.

11:26.722 --> 11:29.186
And God says, look, I've forgiven you.

11:29.246 --> 11:31.188
You're a new creation.

11:31.248 --> 11:34.073
Don't focus on that anymore.

11:35.294 --> 11:37.337
We can get stuck about things we've done wrong.

11:37.357 --> 11:40.482
We can get stuck about things that we've done right and done well.

11:40.702 --> 11:41.804
And rest on that.

11:42.384 --> 11:43.706
Let's raise rest on our laurels.

11:43.786 --> 11:44.507
We can do that.

11:44.848 --> 11:47.552
I think the Apostle Paul gives us much better advice.

11:47.932 --> 11:54.642
The Apostle Paul says in Philippians chapter three, he says, not that I've already obtained this or have already reached the goal.

11:54.914 --> 11:59.320
but I press on to lay hold of that for which Christ has laid hold of me.

11:59.820 --> 12:01.763
Brothers and sisters, I do not consider that.

12:01.783 --> 12:02.904
I've already laid hold of it.

12:03.465 --> 12:17.884
But one thing I lay hold of, forgetting what lies behind and straining towards what lies ahead, I press on towards the goal towards the prize of the heavenly call of God in Christ Jesus.

12:18.545 --> 12:22.770
That's Philippians chapter three and Paul says, forgetting what lies behind.

12:23.330 --> 12:25.873
So I think that's part of what we do as stewards.

12:25.953 --> 12:31.580
We forget what lies behind and we live in the present moment because God calls us to be stewards today.

12:31.620 --> 12:35.084
And we don't get so focused on the future.

12:35.124 --> 12:36.506
Here's my other point.

12:36.886 --> 12:40.571
We don't get so focused on the future that we forget to be stewards today.

12:45.197 --> 12:47.079
Some people think about stewardship that way.

12:47.099 --> 12:49.682
They think, you know, someday I'll be a good steward.

12:50.338 --> 12:53.242
Some day, you know, I'll have money in the bank.

12:53.943 --> 12:55.425
I'll have a stable life.

12:56.386 --> 12:57.287
I'll be settled.

12:57.608 --> 13:02.635
And then after I take care of all this stuff, then God, I'll be a good and faithful steward.

13:04.697 --> 13:13.529
There was a philosophy among philanthropy a few years ago that came out, and some really still hold it and proclaim it.

13:13.569 --> 13:17.234
It's called effective altruism, effective altruism.

13:17.274 --> 13:20.018
It was kind of pushed forward by some of the tech billionaires

13:20.738 --> 13:23.703
Altruism is simply generosity and giving.

13:23.743 --> 13:36.624
Effective means you do it in such a way that it bears fruit, that you give to organizations, nonprofits that are doing good work and are effective in transforming the world.

13:36.864 --> 13:39.027
You give smart and otherwise.

13:40.249 --> 13:45.618
You give smartly, you give strategically, so that your giving will be effective.

13:46.562 --> 13:47.443
And I agree with that.

13:47.644 --> 13:56.035
I think we're called to be good stewards and not waste what God has given us, but give it in such a way that we know we're bearing good fruit with what we give.

13:57.117 --> 14:03.986
The thing was that some in this movement felt like don't give now, just focus on accumulating wealth now.

14:04.848 --> 14:09.935
And then someday you'll have a lot of money and then you'll have a big influence when you start giving.

14:11.938 --> 14:15.122
One of the guys that preached this was

14:15.234 --> 14:17.017
a guy named Sam Bankman Freed.

14:17.577 --> 14:19.060
Do you remember Sam Bankman Freed?

14:19.100 --> 14:22.024
He ran a cryptocurrency exchange.

14:22.865 --> 14:25.649
He was a guy, I remember in the news, big, bushy hair.

14:25.669 --> 14:28.473
He wore t-shirts to the Senate.

14:28.553 --> 14:32.259
I mean, he was also a crook.

14:32.519 --> 14:36.044
You know, we remember that he stole money from the exchanger.

14:36.064 --> 14:40.390
Basically, people entrusted money to him and he took money from here and used it for other things.

14:40.971 --> 14:42.834
And eventually he got found out

14:43.074 --> 14:45.357
and he was sentenced to 25 years in jail.

14:45.418 --> 14:52.448
And I don't think he's a wise person to listen to when it calls it.

14:52.488 --> 14:55.393
Wait till later to give until you have a lot to give.

14:55.413 --> 14:58.798
I think we are meant to start giving now.

14:58.838 --> 15:00.240
That's, I believe that.

15:00.340 --> 15:06.390
And you think, well, Scott, shouldn't we manage our money, save for the future, invest for the future?

15:06.710 --> 15:08.212
And of course we are to do that.

15:08.673 --> 15:11.858
John Wesley, when he spoke to the Methodists,

15:12.642 --> 15:22.272
during the Methodist movement in England there in the 1700s, he preached that Methodist words to earn all they can, save all they can, and give all they can.

15:22.332 --> 15:40.850
We're at a work hard, we're to earn what God enables us to earn, we're to save, we are to be wise and put money aside in the bank and invest it well, but also we're to give, we're to be generous now, not just in the future, but God gives us what we need today so that we can be generous today.

15:42.210 --> 15:45.195
And here's the true reality.

15:46.277 --> 15:48.901
We really don't know what the future holds.

15:52.306 --> 16:01.561
You remember in Luke chapter 12, Jesus told this parable of a rich farmer who had a abundant harvest.

16:02.262 --> 16:05.547
He had so much crops that he didn't know what to do with it all.

16:05.587 --> 16:09.714
He didn't have enough space, and so he tore down his old barns and built

16:10.082 --> 16:13.106
or silos and build bigger ones so that he could store what he had.

16:13.447 --> 16:24.322
And after he did that, he said to himself, wow, you've got it all made, you can now relax and eat, drink, and be merry.

16:25.384 --> 16:27.587
And that's what he said to himself.

16:28.368 --> 16:38.482
And God said to him, you fool this very night, your life is being demanded of you and the things you have prepared.

16:38.978 --> 16:39.900
whose will they be?"

16:39.940 --> 16:46.373
And after telling his disciples this parable, Jesus added the following words.

16:46.734 --> 16:54.730
He said, so does with those who store up for themselves, who store up treasures for themselves but are not rich towards God.

16:54.791 --> 16:57.717
That's the wisdom of Scripture.

16:58.418 --> 17:00.402
We don't know what's going to happen tomorrow.

17:00.930 --> 17:15.064
In fact, the letter at James, in chapter four, it says the following, it says, come now, you who say, today or tomorrow, we will go to such and such a town and spend a year there doing business and making money, yet you do not even know what tomorrow will bring.

17:15.645 --> 17:16.385
What is your life?

17:17.226 --> 17:21.090
For you are a miss that appears for a little while and then vanishes.

17:21.130 --> 17:29.298
Instead, you ought to say if the Lord wishes, we will live and do this or that.

17:29.410 --> 17:32.074
mistake we can make with stewardship is saying, well, I've done it in the past.

17:32.094 --> 17:33.115
I don't need to do it now.

17:33.396 --> 17:38.603
The other mistake we can make is thinking, I'll just do it in the future, even though we don't know what the future holds.

17:39.284 --> 17:41.247
But God gives us what we need today.

17:41.287 --> 17:44.151
So we give thanks for what gives us today.

17:44.231 --> 17:46.615
And we practice generosity stewardship today.

17:48.478 --> 17:49.780
God is faithful today.

17:49.800 --> 17:57.010
And so we're faithful stewards today and this wonderful hymn.

17:57.570 --> 17:58.772
great as thy faithfulness.

17:58.792 --> 18:04.219
You all know that song, great as thy faithfulness, morning by morning, new mercies I see.

18:04.259 --> 18:06.683
That's true, God gives us mercies each morning.

18:06.963 --> 18:16.476
And that song comes out of that great verse in the middle of lamentations, the book of sorrow, but in the middle of lamentation, right at the heart of it, there's the affirmation that God is good.

18:16.496 --> 18:19.841
And it says, the steadfast love of the Lord never ceases.

18:20.302 --> 18:22.224
His mercies never come to an end.

18:22.244 --> 18:24.247
They are new every morning.

18:24.267 --> 18:26.450
Great is your faithfulness.

18:26.594 --> 18:29.558
God gives us what we need to say.

18:30.178 --> 18:32.782
New every morning are God's mercies.

18:33.442 --> 18:50.744
When the Apostle Paul wrote his fundraising letter, his letter of giving to the Corinthians, this is in 2 Corinthians chapter eight and nine, Paul refers to the story of the Israelites in the wilderness and how God fed them manna from heaven, bread from heaven every morning.

18:50.764 --> 18:55.730
If you remember that, every morning they got out and God provided with them bread that was there on the

18:56.706 --> 18:59.769
floor on the ground, and they just had to gather it in.

18:59.789 --> 19:06.056
And it says that those who gathered too much did not have too much, and those who gathered too little did not have too little.

19:06.377 --> 19:08.639
If they tried to hoard it, it became rotten.

19:09.721 --> 19:14.666
But if they only had gathered some, they discovered that was enough for what they needed.

19:14.726 --> 19:17.509
That's God's mercies and faithfulness at work.

19:19.151 --> 19:20.272
God is faithful today.

19:20.312 --> 19:25.298
Here's a video from the Skinner family, from Micah and Katie.

19:25.634 --> 19:30.101
talks about how God is faithful and please watch the video.

19:33.006 --> 19:34.849
I'm Micah Skinner and this is my wife Katie.

19:35.470 --> 19:41.559
And we, actually our daughter Lily started coming here four or five years ago.

19:41.619 --> 19:48.951
Her friend invited her to youth and so for a little while she was coming alone.

19:49.993 --> 19:53.458
And then she just really

19:53.666 --> 20:00.172
fell in love with it and wanted to come and be part of all the services, all the youth events.

20:00.773 --> 20:06.579
And we finally decided we should go as like supporting her.

20:06.639 --> 20:15.307
But I think we kind of thought we would just sneak in the back door, sit in the back row, low key.

20:16.889 --> 20:17.810
But...

20:18.030 --> 20:22.034
I'm not sure who it was, but the word got out that I played music.

20:22.178 --> 20:23.960
quickly got volunteered to play drums.

20:24.881 --> 20:35.592
And kind of went from there, did it as a, you know, kind of just serving, doing my part and showing support for Lily because she started coming to the church.

20:35.612 --> 20:40.537
And the more I did it, the more it started to really affect me in a positive way.

20:42.159 --> 20:45.803
I started to really feel like I was part of a community, part of a church.

20:45.823 --> 20:48.946
And that's something that I wasn't really used to before.

20:49.282 --> 21:04.863
fostering that relationship with everybody here and creating more friendships and relationships with everybody and The more we've done that the more like a community it's felt Beyond just coming to a church.

21:05.384 --> 21:16.178
Yeah, and eventually My whole family started to follow I think it started with Lily's cousins and

21:16.962 --> 21:20.527
they started coming to youth and eventually my brother and sister-in-law did.

21:20.547 --> 21:43.218
So it just, it was like we, my family just slowly started to take over like my sisters started bringing their kids and then our younger kids started attending the children's church when Ms. Rachel started and Lily again fell in love with, you know,

21:43.778 --> 21:46.881
any and every opportunity to volunteer with the kids.

21:47.041 --> 21:56.951
And she tells me still to this day after going to all the camp boll glens, all the worship arts camps, that it's the happiest that she is is when she's working with the kids.

21:57.531 --> 22:13.106
And to me that's been so monumental is having other people that are so invested in your kids and genuinely care about them and their relationship with God and two of our kids

22:13.474 --> 22:18.299
have gotten baptized of their own accord.

22:18.439 --> 22:26.989
I mean, in the middle of a service at two different times, they each ask to come up and get baptized and that just blew me away.

22:27.049 --> 22:42.866
My sister, Sarah, has been volunteering at the thrift store, which has just spoken volumes to our family because she has this amazing little group of women that love her

22:43.010 --> 22:55.743
and appreciate her hard work and just, you know, have given her this gift that in turn has just blessed our family as well.

22:57.865 --> 23:00.447
But now my dad's playing on the worship team.

23:00.507 --> 23:11.538
Mike is up there and Lily's on the youth worship team and singing on Sundays and I finally started going to Bible studies

23:12.834 --> 23:15.036
getting involved where I could.

23:15.076 --> 23:20.842
And it's just, it's turned into like wanting to be here as much as we can, like a joke.

23:21.362 --> 23:24.125
He wishes he could quit his job here full time.

23:24.145 --> 23:27.489
And I'll never forget one day he looked at me.

23:27.529 --> 23:31.012
He goes, I want to start tithing here.

23:31.052 --> 23:41.042
And I almost fell over just because I don't know that was his, that was his like level of seriousness of wanting to be here permanently.

23:41.314 --> 24:08.754
Even beyond like whenever I first started playing drums here, my excuse was I'm that's my time is I'll devote my time I'll devote my my energies towards volunteering in the music and any other way that I can serve but the more time I spend here the more I start to believe in the mission of this church like everything about it the mission statement every just every day I see more and more ways that the church

24:08.994 --> 24:12.078
and everybody in the church is serving the community around them.

24:12.658 --> 24:14.220
And that's something that I believe in.

24:14.240 --> 24:19.667
It's beyond just words, it's beyond just a Sunday service.

24:20.328 --> 24:21.549
It's every single day.

24:21.629 --> 24:28.237
And the more that I get involved with things, I mean doing the kids camp and just participating in that.

24:28.277 --> 24:35.666
And then the youth lock in too, staying up all night, which is something I haven't done since I was probably in my early 20s.

24:36.322 --> 24:42.931
So when I first started coming, there's always been a relationship with God.

24:43.411 --> 24:49.760
I've always, I've grown up in church my whole life, always had that influence in my life.

24:49.780 --> 24:58.271
But I think there was a real difference that happened when I started coming here and started serving on the worship team.

24:58.291 --> 25:00.835
Because music has always been something that's spoken to me.

25:00.855 --> 25:06.322
It's always been something that's enriched and uplifted me.

25:07.010 --> 25:14.137
So doing that naturally started to pull me in that direction back to a more real relationship with God.

25:14.197 --> 25:35.858
I've been feeling closer to Him any time I'm up on stage playing, whether it's guitar or drums, finding myself getting lost in that and lost in that worship and lost in the realness of God and being able to feel Him again, which is something that I hadn't felt in a really long time.

25:36.290 --> 25:45.101
It's easy to see it individually with the people around me through conversation that it's sort of like it's happening individually and among everyone as a whole.

25:45.201 --> 25:58.036
You can feel it, you can sense it that the church is moving in this new direction that feels really powerful, but it's almost like a subtle, real, deep change.

25:58.677 --> 26:02.642
Watching him and then also Lily has

26:03.618 --> 26:06.141
been very transformative for me.

26:06.161 --> 26:26.543
I also grew up in church, but it was like a slow deepening for me when we got here because the teachings are so, so wonderfully laid out to live out in a practical way.

26:26.663 --> 26:33.330
And so for me, there wasn't a disconnect anymore between what we're sitting and listening to in church

26:33.506 --> 26:35.429
what we're told to live out at home.

26:35.549 --> 27:03.026
The connection between the two became so real and then we started doing the bible recap and that really transformed my view of God and what what he really is and his love for us and all of that was just like this very very slow quiet deepening that I didn't even recognize was happening but

27:04.610 --> 27:15.026
It has drawn me to Him and drawn me to want to be in His presence and hear as often as we can be.

27:19.974 --> 27:22.698
Thank you, Katie and Micah, for the wonderful testimony.

27:23.059 --> 27:25.703
You've heard how God is faithful to us today.

27:25.743 --> 27:27.706
God's been faithful in the past.

27:28.046 --> 27:30.450
We celebrate that and rejoice in that.

27:30.722 --> 27:37.852
But we don't just focus on the past and get stuck in the past because God is faithful today, and God will be faithful in the future.

27:38.072 --> 27:44.021
We trust that, but we don't get so focused on the future that we forget to be present in the present.

27:45.042 --> 27:48.968
God is faithful yesterday, today, and forever.

27:49.689 --> 27:50.850
God is faithful to us today.

27:50.911 --> 27:56.178
So we are stewards, faithful stewards with what God trusts to us today.

